GPCR signaling is terminated by the family of regulator of G-protein signaling (RGS) proteins, the function of which has mainly been attributed to their ability to interact with G- subunits of heterotrimeric G proteins. RGS proteins are GAPs that enhance the rate of GTP hydrolysis of G- subunits.
Common GPCR signaling pathways include Gi-mediated cyclic AMP inhibition.

CCRL2 binds the chemokine CCL19 with an affinity similar to the binding of CCL19 to its other receptor CCR7. CCRL2 may have a role in modulating chemokine-triggered immune responses by capturing and internalizing CCL19.

Fractalkine is the only known chemokine shown tomediate strong cell adhesion mediated viain vitrobindingto its receptor, a member of the TM7 family of receptors. Monocytes, natural killer cells, T cells, and microglia express the CX3CR1 receptor, migrate in response to fractalkine, and adhere to immobilized fractalkine in vitro.
CXCR2 (High affinity interleukin-8 receptor B) (Murphy PM and Tiffany HL, 1991) is closely related to CXCR1 and binding of IL-8 to the receptor causes activation of neutrophils.

CXCL2 (MIP2-alpha;Gro-beta;Gro-2) (Iida N and Grotendorst GR, 1990; Haskill S et al, 1990) is closely related to CXCL1 (90% amino acid sequence). It is secreted by monocytes and macrophages and attracts polymorphonuclear leukocytes and hematopoietic stem cells.

CXCL1 (previously known as GRO1 oncogene; NAP-3; MSGA-alpha) (Richmond A et al, 1988) is expressed by neutrophils, macrophages and epithelial cells and possesses neutrophil chemoattractant activity. It is secreted by melanoma cells and is implicated in melanoma pathogenesis.
Macrophage migration inhibitory factor (MIF) is an evolutionary conserved cytokine with proinflammatory functions, and has also been claimed to be a non-canonical CXCR2 ligand.
